            "answer_text": "This is what mathematicians sometimes call an \u201cabuse of notation.\u201d To be sure, they use that phrase somewhat affectionately. Here\u2019s the deal: If [math]X[/math] is a finite set, then the power set of [math]X[/math] has [math]2^{|X|}[/math] elements. It\u2019s nice notation, so they extend it beyond the context where it originally made sense \u2014 that is, they extend it to the infinite case. Without that extra definition, [math]2^{|X|}[/math] doesn\u2019t mean the same thing when [math]X[/math] is finite or infinite. In particular, that notation doesn\u2019t make obvious sense when [math]X[/math] is infinite. For example, I\u2019m not aware of a way to extend the notation to the full scope of what you can do with real-number exponents. I don\u2019t know what [math](1+X)^{Y/2}[/math] means when [math]X[/math] and [math]Y[/math] are infinite sets, for example. ",
