            "answer_text": "In cardinal arithmetic the cardinality of the set of functions from the set [math]Y[/math] to the set [math]X[/math] is denoted [math]|X|^{|Y|}[/math]. For finite sets this corresponds exactly to Natural number exponentiation. There is a simple bijection between the power set, [math]\\mathcal P(Y)[/math], and the set of functions from [math]Y[/math] to [math]\\{0,1\\}[/math] given by whether an element is in the subset. That is: [math]\\quad F\\in\\mathcal P(Y)\\leftrightarrow f(y)=\\begin{cases}0&\\text{if $y\\notin F$}\\\\1&\\text{if $y\\in F$}\\end{cases}[/math] Since [math]|\\{0,1\\}|=2[/math] we have [math]|\\mathcal P(Y)|=2^{|Y|}[/math]. Note that for any finite [math]n\\in\\mathbb N[/math] greater than [math]1[/math], and any non-finite [math]|Y|\\colon n^{|Y|}=2^{|Y|}[/math] (as Cardinal numbers). ",
